Both the DS model and DA model are backscattering models that cannot describe the case of localization due to an energy barrier characterized by a barrier height (Eh) and hopping time (τh) (scheme in Fig. 3). The thermally-assisted hopping time can be expressed as τh = τsexp(Eh/kBT). When Eh → 0, τh reduces to the Drude scattering time τs. In this case, the photoconductivity response can be expressed by the Drude–Lorentz model (DL model):10ΔσDLω=Nq2m*1−ϕτs1−iωτs+ϕωτhω−iτh(ω2−ωh2),ωh=Ehℏ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
